item.title: Grandpa Puckett
item.description:
Hi everyone, I'm MrPuckett My dad died this weekend.
I moved to Minnesota last year after he was diagnosed with alzheimers. Watching him slowly fade away was one of the toughest things I've ever been a part of. But I don't want to tell you about his death, I want to tell you why he was the greatest human being I've ever known.
When I was first homeless I was in Seatttle, Washington Nobody knew I was struggling with addiction, I was so ashamed I didn't even tell my dad
He found out from a mutual acquaintance what was happening and at 70 years old he - Hopped on the first plane from Minneapolis to Seattle Rented a car Drove to the junkie park I was sleeping at Woke me and my dog up And after giving me the biggest hug I've ever gotten, he drove me to Minnesota and took care of my dog as I went into rehab.
That wasn't the first or last time he'd save my life One of my first personal posts ever on Imgur was my story of PCP addiction My dad found me in a St Paul hospital after police picked me up sleeping on the side of the road in below 0 temptatures, rescued my dog from the city pound and got me all the help I needed to survive.
We moved a lot when I was a kid. When we moved to the U.P. of Michigan it was too late for me to get on a soccer team. The league said if we can find a coach then a whole new team could be formed and I could play. My dad spent the next years of his life learning everything he could about soccer, there was no question - he was a coach now so that me and a couple dozen other kids could play.
That's just the kind of guy he was, and you didn't need to be family. He helped people before they asked for it, he'd give you the shirt off his fucking back before he'd ever let you be chilly He was my only role model, the only one I ever needed, and now he's gone.
I'd be lying if I said there wasn't some relief there too. Watching someone you love lose every memory they've ever had, lose their ability to take care of themselves in the most basic of ways with no cure It's absolutely heart wrenching, and it's not the way he ever wanted to say goodbye.
But even though he forgot how to brush his teeth, use the television and even tie his shoes He knew who my fiancee and I were right until the very last day and was always full of joy when we were near
It's been a tough few days trying to plan and afford all the after-life things like the funeral. The grieving comes in waves but only in-between taking care of everything that needs to be done now. Luckily my job has been understanding with time off.
I didn't want to move to Minnesota last year but in hindsight I'm really lucky I did My dad looked forward to every phone call, every visit, every delusional conversation about how the Vikings could win the superbowl
Now that he's gone I've been trying to think of ways to not only honor his amazing life but also how to try and help others with alzheimers The first thing I did was sign up for a 70 mile bike race - The Ride To End ALZ
I've never ridden more than 10 miles before but my dad was always so impressed and supportive with my running I know he would be proud of this It also gives me the chance to fundraise for an incredible alzheimers non-profit in his name and memory.
The best way to honor him now is to live a life that he would've been proud of And I intend to do that every day for as long as I live.
I miss you dad, I'm grateful for everything you ever did and every time you were ever there for me. It's not the same without you man. ... If you'd like to help the Alzheimers Assocation fund research to help families with this brutal disease, you can do so in my dad's honor here - http://act.alz.org/goto/GrandpaPuckett
